2.6-2.7 Create a plot with the mpg data

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) +
  labs(x = "Engine size (L)", y = "Fuel efficiency (mpg)")

This graph has engine size on the x-axis, fuel efficiency on the y-axis, and point color correlates to the class/type of car.

What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name?

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ < 5)) +
  labs(x = "Engine size (L)", y = "Fuel efficiency (mpg)")

This changes the color of the points based on whether the engine size is greater than or less than 5 L.

2.9 Facet and panel plots

Facet the plot using a single variable: facet_wrap()

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Separates by car type/class. Nrow() dictates how many rows of graphs there are (2). Ncol(2) would return two columns of graphs rather than 2 rows.

Facet the plot using more than one variable: facet_grid()

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Separates by # of cylinders and by drive type.
